{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600647/1930072001/0210.xml":{"full_text":"Special Articles\nPart 2\u2014B Pages\nMUSSOLINI SEEN RUBBING\nSORE SPOTS OF EUROPE\nHis Support of Peace Treaty Revision\nDeclared Opening Way to\nEndless Friction.\nBY FRANK H. SIMONDS.\nT would be difficult to Imagine any\nI move at once more daring, more\ndangerous and in itself more in\ncongruous than that disclosed in\nMussolini\u2019s recent interview in a\nFrench newspaper, the Petit Parisien.\nThis paper, by the bye. has the largest\ncirculation, not merely of any French\nJournal, but of any daily in the world.\nIn this interview the Duce squarely\naligned himself and his country on the\nside of a revision of the peace treaties\nOs Paris.\nThis declaration instantly calls into\nquestion the whole framework of ex\nisting European order and peace. As\na move in the great Italian game of\nundermining and destroying the pres\nent French supremacy on the conti\nnent it must be conceded to be both\nan adroit and, from the French point\nof view, a dangerous if not a deadly I\nthrust.\nWhat Mussolini is up to is obvious\nThe peace treaties resulted in the forci\nble separation from the defeated states\nof large areas and many millions of\npeople. The victims of this far-reach\ning change were Germany, Austria,\nHungary and Bulgaria. After the Rus\nsian revolution and the later Russo-\nPolish conflict, Russia also lost vast\nterritories extending from the Arctic to\nthe Black Sea. Thus from 1920 on\nward Europe has been divided between\nthe nations which were satisfied with\nthe decisions of Paris\u2014France, Ru\nmania, Czechoslovakia, Jugoslavia.\nPoland and Belgium\u2014and those which\ndemanded revision.\nItaly Gained by War.\nTtie incongruous detail in the Fascist\ndictator\u2019s present maneuvers lies pre\ncisely in the fact that, along with the\nother victor states, Italy benefited at'\nthe expense of the defeated nations, i\nand today holds in the Upper Adige\nancient Austrian territory containing a\nconsiderable Teutonic population. Be\nhind Trieste she has taken other Aus\ntrian lands which are inhabited by a\nSlav majority unreconciled to the an\nnexation. while at Flume she possesses\n\u2022he town which was once the unique\nseaport of Hungary and is now the\nobject of Southern Slav aspirations.\nItaly, then, most certainly does not\ndesire a revision of the peace treaties in\nthe sense that Germany, Hungary or\nBulgaria asks for it. Any revision based\nupon the principle of self-determina\ntion would mean for the Italians not a\ngain but a loss of area and popula\ntion. On the other hand, the Italian\nclaim is that Italy came out of the\npeace conference a victim of her recent\nallies. The revision of the peace which\nItaly asks is not a restoration of terri\ntories unjustly taken, of which she pos\nsesses a fair share, but a redivision of\nspoils.\nNevertheless, the Italian proposal\nmust awaken endless repercussions. In\nrecent months, as, in fact, ever since\nthe Fascist revolution, Mussolini has\nbeen making strenuous efforts to bring\nabout a German-ItaJian combination.\nAll Germans agrgg that .the jPolish Cor\nridor must be suppressed and Poland\nforced to restore to Prussia the present\ndistrict of Pomerelia, former German\nWest Prussia, and to assent to the re\nturn of Danzig to German sovereignty.\nMeans New Partition.\nPoland, strongly backed by France,\nnaturally refuses all such surrender,\nwhich would mean for the new republic\n\u25a0till another partition. Up to the pres\nent time in Germany the policy of\nSresemann. which envisaged peace and\nrejected all dangerous adventures, has\nprevailed. But Stresemann is dead, the\nGerman Nationalists are growing\nstronger and never ceasing to demand\na revision of the peace treaties. Musso\nlini is thus making an open and delib\nerate bid for the support of the mon\narchical as contrasted with the republi\ncan elements in Germany.\nIn the same way he is bidding for\nHungarian co-operation, for Hungary\nIs resolved to recover the lands taken\nfrom her by the treaty of Trianon and\nbestowed upon Rumania, Jugoslavia\nCzechoslovakia, all three the allies of\nFrance. Finally in the Balkins Italy\nis angling for the favors of Bulgaria,\nwhich stQl purposes to recover Mace\ndonia. That country is now in the\nmain in the hands of Jugoslavia. Ita\nly\u2019s chief opponent and France\u2019s first\nfriend in the Near East.\nBy contrast all French policy rests\nupon the resolve to maintain the status\nquo created by the peace treaties, be\ncause any modification must in the end\nresult in enormous accession of German\npower and in the immediate diminu- j\ntion of the actual territory of the al\nlies of France and eventually in the\ngrave loss of French influence and pres\ntige. What France fears above all is\nthat the suppression of the Polish Cor\nridor and the union of Austria with\nGermany would lead directly to the\nrestoration of that German Mitteleu\nropa which was momemntarily in ex\nistence during the World War and was\nat the back of the dreams of many\nGermans even before 1914.\nRisky Policy Is Seen.\nOs course, it must be clear how risky\nIs the Italian play. If one assume that\nthe Anschluss will be realized and Aus\ntria joined to the Reich, nothing is\nmore inevitable than that Hungary will\nnot joyfully but necessarily fall into\nArt Jury in Paris Accepts Work\nOs Janies G. Bailey, U. S. Diplomat\nThat presidents of leading banks have\naften started their careers as newsboys\nis a story so frequent that nobody thinks\nof even expressing surprise or admira\ntion when it is told. But that a man\nwho has been in the diplomatic service\nfor many years should suddenly make a\npublic appearance as a painter gives a j\nnew angle on this curious problem of i\nprofession and avocation. i\nJabes G. Bailey of Kentucky, who has\npassed through six revolutions in the.\ncourse of his long years in the service\nof the United States abroad, has just\nhad a picture accepted by the Spring\nSalon in Paris. It is the first time he\nhas submitted one of his paintings to a\njury and it will be the first time that\nany of his paintings are hung in public.\nMr. Bailey, as a young man, was con\nnected with State politics and with edu\ncation. He was principal of a high\nschool, a professor of government and\nliterature and thence turned to politics, i\nHe served as member of the Kentucky\nLegislature, in which he was chairman\nof the committee on education. His rep\nutation at that time was that of a bril\nliant speaKer. He was the best orator\nof the rising young men in Kentucky, i\nGradually his Interests centered to-\nward Washington and more than 30\nyears ago he entered the diplomatic\nservice. During his long career he went j\nthrough six revolutions, several in South\nAmerica, two in Portugal and finally the\nRussian revolution. He left Mexico just\nbefore the fall of Diaz. Before the out\nbreak of the World War he was a mem\nber of the international conference on\nbills of exchange at The Hague as well\nr s member of the administrative council\nI the German orientation. Nor is it less\nlikely that, once this Greater Germany\nhas become a fact, there will be an\nalmost irresistible pressure of the new\nj German Empire to recover Trieste and\nthus a gateway on the Adriatic, while\nsentimental and racial considerations\nw ill combine to render the question of\nI the Upper Adige acute.\nMussolini is playing for a German al\nliance to break the preseint French su\ni premacy on the Continent. So far he\nhas been unsuccessful, because he has\nfailed to detach the Central European\nstates allied with France and sharing\nthe French determination to maintain i\nthe status quo of Paris. And he has\nbeen equally unsuccessful in enlisting\nGerman co-operation, because Germany\nremains bitterly resentful of the Ital\nian desertion of 1914-15.\nHaving so far failed alike at Berlin\nand in Bucharest, Belgrade and Prague,\nI Mussolini has come out into the open\nand declared for a revision of the peace\ntreaties in terms which must arouse\ninterest and revive and strengthen\nhopes in Berlin, Budapest, Sofia, even\nin Moscow-, where any attempt to upset\npeace and order and precipitate con\nfusion is necessarily welcome.\nAnother Danger Cited.\nAnother danger of the Italian play:\nEven if Germany should presently join\nin, the result would be to replace a\nweak Austria by a vastly strengthened\nGermany at the frontier of the Alps\nand to insure that not Italian but Ger\nman influence would presently be pre\ndominant from Vienna to Athens. That\nthe new Italian policy might destroy\nFrench influence and prestige in Eu\nrope is patent, but that Italy can profit\nby such a game is less clear.\nOs course, in estimating Italian pol\nj icy it is necessary to avoid the error of\ngiving lasting importance to any single\nman. At bottom the Duce is an op\nportunist and while he seems today to\nbe making a decisive gesture toward\nthe defeated and dissatisfied peoples, it\nis just as possible to .see in his move a\ndefinitive warning to France and to her\nallies, a warning indicative of the dan\ngers which may flow from a further\nrefusal to listen to Italian demands.\nManifestly, then, the Duce is Ashing in\ntroubled waters. He is indulging in a\ndouble play, which on the one hand\nmay enlist the dissatisfied powers in a\nnew combination to break down French\ncontrol or, on the other, at last per\nsuade the French to listen to Italy and\nagree to the demands of Rome, which\nenvisage not a revision of the territorial\nstatus of the Continent of Europe, but\na re-shuffling of colonial territories.\nFor the moment, perhaps, a transfer of\nthe Syrian mandate from France to\nItaly might suffice.\nFrench Position Analyzed.\nThat France will listen to such a\nthreat and make new concessions is, of\ncourse, very unlikely. On the other\nhand the Italian maneuver comes at\na very awkward moment for the French.\nWith the evacuation of the Rhineland\ncompleted, the French hold on Ger-\nmany has become almost non-existent.\nGermany is at last free to act and she\nmay seize upon the present Franco-\nItalian tension, not to associate herself\nwith Italy, but to drive her own bargain\nwith France.\nLaying aside all more or less specu\nlative comment, however, it is clear that\nthe Italian move has served to bring\nto the fore once more the whole ques\ntion of the existing territorial status\nand political combinations in Europe.\nThe possibility that the Continent will\nnow settle down for a period of recov\nery and the New Europe of the peace\ntreaties take enduring form is much\nslighter Mussolini\u2019s voice raised for\nrevision will revive the questions of the\nPolish Corridor, the Anschluss, of Up\nper Silesia, Vilna, Bessarabia, Transyl\nvania and the Banat, Slovakia, Croatia\nand Macedonia. Deliberately the Duce\nhas rubbed every sore spot in Europe.\nWhat must be perceived, too, is that\nin taking this course the Duce is not in\nthe least interested in the principle\nwhich he has invoked, which, so far as\nthe Continent is concerned, would if\nfairly applied result in grave territorial\nand strategic loss for his own country.\nWhat he is doing is exploiting the griev\nances of the defeated nations for Italian\nends with the chief purpose of weaken\ning the French situation on the Conti\nnent.\nEurope Arming Again.\nThe justification of Mussolini\u2019s vari\nous moves must be discovered in the\npatent truth that as long as the exist\ning endures, Italy cannot play the\nrole of a great power in Europe or rival\nFrench influence. The system of peace\nwhich exists in Europe today is a\nFrench system and for Fascist aspira\ntions, for the realization of the dream\nof a New Rome, the destruction of the\nsystem is a necessary step.\nNo one can mistake the risks of\nItalian policy. By the new maneuver\nMussolini has made possible, if not cer\ntain, the redivision of Europe into\narmed camps. The peace of Europe is\nbecoming increasingly precarious. More\nover, it is a mournful reflection that the\nrecent rapid accentuation of bitterness\nand unrest is the direct consequence of\nthe London Naval Conference, designed\nto advance the cause of peace by for\nwarding the task of disarmament.\n(Copyright, 1930.)\nof the International Court of Arbitra\ntion.\n\u201cBut for 40 years I have been paint\ning. 1 he explained when questioned in\nhis Paris home, where he has been liv\ning for some years, \"when other men\nwent hunting or slung golf clubs across\ntheir shoulders for a day of golf. I took\nmy paint box and a sketching block.\u201d\nMr. Bailey's work reflects a profound\nlove and appreciation of nature. His\n1 pictures are extraordinarily colorful and\nat the same time most delicate in color.\nTrees, sky, water, chiefly inspire his\nbrush He admits frankly that portraits\ndo not interest him much, although he\nhas made a number. The Paris Salon\njury is the first to accord official recog\nnition of a talent which has taken years\nto develop and has hidden itself modest\nly until it was mature and ready for the\npublic.\nVillage Church Choir\nPuts Ban on Bobbed Hair\nThe village of Bremnes near Hauge\nsund on the west coast of Norway\nscored a record when the church au\nthorities recently refused to permit\nI women with cropped hair to sing in\nthe church\u2019s choir. \"Cropping and\nundulation are an abomination,\u201d says\nthe leader of the church, and though\nthe parish belongs to the state and the\nbishop has declared that the local coun\ncil has no right to censure other peo\nple\u2019s personal tastes in such matters as\nhairdressing, the unique ruling has not\nbeen repealed so far.\nEDITORIAL SECTION\nshe puntlaij Pfetf.\n1\nI New Light on the Kaiser j\nNoted American Tells of the Life Led by Former Ruler of Germany at Doom, Holland.\nKAISER IN UNIFORM IN HIS\nEXILE.\nNote\u2014This it the Ant of a teriet of\nthree articlei written bti Mr. Bigelow,\nwho. wan a recent ouett of the former\nKaiter. In these articles the reader gets\nan interesting insight into the life and\nthoughts of the former German ruler.\nBY POULTNEY BIGELOW.\nDOORN, Holland.\u2014The Kaiser Is\na poor man, and his poverty\nis doubly keen, for by nature\nhe is both generous and hos\npitable. Poverty is not easy to\nde.lne; but in a general way we call\nourselves poor whenever compelled to\nreduce our expenses or drop from ore\nfinancial plane to a lower one.\nNapoleon seemed poor in his princi\npality of Elba, for he had been the\nruler of all Europe; he seemed poorer\nat St. Helana, although still surrounded\nby servants and courtiers who humored\nhim. In my home town on the Hud\nson a man is poor if he has no car,\nand a woman Is pitied if she cannot\ndress in silk.\nDoor Prison to Kaiser.\nThe poverty of the Kaiser is, there\nfore, merely relative\u2014his powers of en\ntertaining have shrunk; he cannot\nmake the costly presents that he for\nmerly did. His magnificent yacht has\ndisappeared. He told me that he did\nnot know anything of its present\nwhereabouts, or even existence. All he\nknew was that it had been pillaged by\nthe revolutionary mob in 1918 and, of\n\u25a0course, he had lost many precious pos\nsessions\u2014all his uniforms, pictutfa,\nkeepsakes, etc.\nDoom is a beautiful country resi\ndence, in my eyes\u2014for I am accustomed\nto the homes about Malden-on-Hud\nDISSOLUTION OF REICHSTAG\nIS HELD NATURAL COURSE\nCrisis Follows Attempt to Rule Ger\nmany Without Help of\nSocialist Faction.\nBY DR. GUSTAV STOLPER,\nNoted German Editor and Economist.\nBERLIN. \u2014The serious political\ncrisis into which Germany\nplunged this week, with the dis\nsolution of the Reichstag, will\nhave many harmful effects, but\nit is nevertheless a natural develep\nment in the as yet unfinished process\nof building up the German state.\nGermany can be ruled only through\nan understanding between the bour\ngeois and the laboring class. The\nSocialist party represents the largest\npart of the laboring class. With its\nhelp, the parties of the Center created\nthe Weimar constitution and defended\nit later against the Nationalists.\nStresemann Strove for Unity.\nThe late Foreign Minister Strese\nmann did much to keep the Right wing\nof the bougeois People's party, to\nwhich he belonged, together with the\nLeft and to prevent its going over to\nthe Nationalists. But, under the\npressure of an unfavorable economic\nsituation, aggravated by mistakes in\nfinancial policy and by an insufficient\nlightening of Germany\u2019s load under\nthe Young reparations plan, a com\npromise between the workmen's de\nmands and the bourgeois classes be\ncame steadily more difficult. The re\nsult was the collapse, at the beginning\nof May, of the Mueller cabinet, which\nincluded both Socialist and Bourgeois\nparty members.\nThe government of the new chan\ncellor, Heinrich Bruening, who be\nlongs to the Catholic Center, repre\nsented an attempt to govern without\nthe Socialists. To this end Bruening\ndesired to gain the support of the Ger\nman Nationalists, who were Dr. Strese\nmann's chief opponents. In order to\nwin them to his policies, Chancellor\nBruening extended a program of aid\nfor the agriculturists, who are es\npecially represented by this party, far\nbeyond the measures planned by the\nMueller government.\nBruening Succeeded at Firat.\nBruening\u2019s plan succeeded at first.\nBut his cabinet's financial policies were\nquite as bad as those of the Mueller\ngovernment and they were aggravated\nby the deepening international eco\nnomic depression. Events progressed to\nthe point where Bruening and his min\nisters were neither able to defend them\nselves successfully against the Socialist\nopposition nor to attract enough mod\nerates to their support from the ex\ntreme right Wing of the Nationalists,\nled by Dr. Alfred Hugenberg.\nThe Bruening government\u2019s plan to\nreform unemployment insurance at a\nhuge saving contained a number of good\nideas, but also, on the other hand, so\nmany unnecessary hardships that it\noffered the Socialists many points of\nattack. Still worse was the fact that\nthe government did not dare admit to\nthe Reichstag that the deficit in the\nbudget was actually 1,500,000,000 marks\n(about (360,000,000), but clung to the\nfiction that it was only 800,000,000\n(about (192.000.000). On top of this\ncame a series of unpopular and eco\nnomically damaging tax proposals, in\ncluding a poll tax which contemplated\nassessing at least 6 marks per capita\non all citizens, almost without any re\ngard for their economic situation, age\nor ability to work.\nWASHINGTON, D. C., SUNDAY MORNING, JULY 20, 1930,\nTHE KAISER AND HIS WIFE AT DOORN.\nson. In the eyes of the Kaiser it must\nseem a narrow prison compared to his\nformer vast estates in different parts\nof Germany, any one of which would\nallow him to tramp all day without ex\nhausting its limits. Here his radius is\nlittle more than the length of one or\ntwo transatlantic liners, and If he\nshould stroll beyond his front gate he\nwould be a target for the cameras of\ntourists, who now hover incessantly\nabout this pretty village.\nI am richer than the Kaiser, because\nI can put more money in the savings\nbank at the close of each fiscal year;\nI can dress like a hired man and I\ncan do my own work, and when the\nSummer boarders come for my auto\ngraph I can tell them that I\u2019m sick\nupstairs\u2014of a contagious disease. And\nthus I am richer than William 11.\nExpenses Run High.\nTherefore, I repeat that the Kaiser is\na poor man; if you first deduct his over\nhead expenses\u2014his indispensable outlay\n\u2014before he can spend one cent upon\nhimself.\nHe has 19 different royal families\nfor whom he considers himself morally\nresponsible since the war and, however\nsimply they manage to live, they never\ntheless represent a heavy and contin\nuous drain upon his purse. Moreover,\nhe cannot help being today the most\nWhen the cabinet found no majority\nfor this tax measure it tried to put its\nprogram into effect through article 48\nof the Weimar constitution, which gives\nthe government extraordinary powers In\nthe event that public security is men\naced. But since public security, happily,\nwas not menaced anywhere in Ger\nmany, this twisting of the constitution\naroused Justified indignation, and the\nSocialists moved in the Reichstag\nthat the decree be immediately re\nscinded. Bruening refused to accede\nto Hugenberg\u2019s conditions for support\ning the government, hence the majority\nof the Nationalists voted against the\ngovernment and the Socialist motion\nwas passed. The chancellor thereupon\ndissolved the Reichstag under the au\nthority of article 48.\nThe people now hope that the new\nelections will return sensible repre\nsentatives to the Reichstag in both the\nSocialist and Bourgeois groups, who\ncan succeed in reaching an agreement\nand effecting the financial and eco\nnomic reforms that the country needs\nso badly.\n(Copyright. 1930.\nIceland Plans Heating of Capital\nThrough Utilization of Hot Springs\nIceland, world's oldest republic, lying\njust south of the Arctic Circle, Is pre\nparing to heat its capital, Reykjavik,\nand at the same time provide power and\namusement through the long Winters\nwith boiling water drawn from nearby\nhot springs.\nProgress in this undertaking to a\npoint where next Winter the national\nhospital and a school will be heated\nand an Indoor swimming pool will be\nestablished, utilizing the water after It\nhas given up most of its heat, was re\nported to the Department of Commerce\nthis week by North Wlnship, consul\ngeneral at Reykjavik. He described it\nas the first step toward heating all of\nthe capital.\nThe success of this undertaking pro\nvides a fresh explanation of the ad\nmiration which anthropologists and\nother students of human races and\nprogress have long expressed for the\nIcelanders, who have retained In their\nIsolation the splendid qualities displayed\nby their ancestors 1,000 years ago In\nresisting oppression at home until hope\nlessly outnumbered, and then sailing\ninto unknown seas in flimsy ships to\nfind a land where they could live in\nfreedom.\nIceland was formed, after a fashion,\nmuch as the republic was formed,\nthrough a volcanic uprising in the\nearth's crust. That accounts for the\nabundance of hot springs there, provid\ning water ranging from warm to boiling\nin temperature. Experiments looking to\nthe use of this natural resource have\nbeen in progress for some years and\nhave shown very favorable results, Mr.\nWlnship reported.\nFirst drillings were made two years\nago by the Icelandic Engineering Asso\nciation at Wash Springs, about 2 miles\nfrom the capital. During the suceeed\ninteresting figure In modern history and\na target for innumerable appeals from\nhistorians and others of note who seek\nlight on the events of his remarkable\nreign.\nHe must either leave all such appeals\nunnoticed or he must spend money out\nof his own purse in maintaining a ref\nerence library or bureau of archives\nand secretaries competent in that field.\nA President of the United States, nota\nbly such a one as Ulysses S. Grant, was\nbombarded with requests for informa\ntion on disputed points, and this bom\nbardment continued long after he had\nleft office. How much more then Is\nthis true of a Kaiser, who for more\nthan 40 years has been the subject of\ncontroversy throughout the world?\nChateau Too Small for Guests.\nWe were shown to a comfortable\nsuite of rooms\u2014a parlor, with two bed\nrooms adjoining, and, of course, the\nusual bath room, etc. Our windows gave\nus on all sides views of beautiful park\nland\u2014windows that we call French, al\nthough they are common throughout\ncontinental Europe. The Kaiser lodges\nhis guests in a separate building, for\nhis own chateau has not the requisite\nspace.\nThis again Is relative; but my read\ners probably have in mind a hundred\nrich Americans whose country homes\nFRENCH OPINION OF U. S.\nFOUND HIGHLY FAVORABLE\nNewspaper Clippings Give Wrong Appre\nciation Due to Crime News and Con\ntrasts With Uniformity of Daily Life\nBY GERVILLE REACHE,\nOn. es the Foremost Journalists ot France.\nPARIS. \u2014As a general rule the\nFrench state of mind toward\nAmericans is not correctly ap\npreciated in the United States.\nThe relations between the two\ncountries are somewhat warped by the\npress clippings transmitted daily.\nWhen one opens a newspaper today\none sees therein scarcely anything other\nthan crimes and felonies, accidents and\nincidents, and one might suppose that\nlife consists only of perpetual tragedies,\nwhereas in reality, tragedy is the excep\ntion which contrasts with the uni\nformity of daily life. Similarly In rela\ntions between peoples, what is reported\nrelates mostly to divergences of views,\nto anxieties and to clouds; these re\nports fail to indicate the current\nthoughts.\nNow, truth compels the statement\nthat there exists in France a veritable\nInfatuation for the United States and a\nvery great curiosity concerning its his\ntory, its magnificent development and\neven its popular tas cs.\nj lng experiments the hot water was suc\ncessfully used in heating a house, in\ncooking and washing and In warming\nI the soil. Further investigation and ex\ni perimentation are planned.\nr Under the plan for heating the capi\ntal a pumping plant will be constructed\nk near Wash Springs. It will be built\nl underground, and the natural hot water\n1 will be conducted first to a large storage\ntank and thence forced to the city\nthrough pipes carefully insulated to pre\nvent escape of the heat. At the end of\ni the pipe line a pressure regulator will\n1 be installed and connected with electric\npumps to be operated according to re\nqulrements. The line will terminate in\nan air tank to assure an even flow.\nConstruction of a storage tank in the\ncity to take care of surplus water dur\ning the night, preventing waste and at\nthe same time enhancing the effective\nness of the system, is contemplated\nearly next year.\nThe pipe system in the buildings to\nbe heated with the spring water, Mr.\nWlnship explained, will be installed in\nthe usual manner, except that the radi\nators will be somewhat larger than or\ndinary. The head flow will be fed by\nan Injector and the water will leave\nthe return pipes through a valve which\nwill act to keep the system full. Be\ntween the flow and the return a by-pass\nwill permit the feed water to be mixed\nwith the return water for regulating the\ntemperature in the radiators.\nAfter serving its heating purposes the\nreturn water will be directed into the\nindoor swimming pool. This can be ex\npected to become quite center of\nactivity during the Winters, which, with\nthe ground Arm underfoot instead of\nslushy and muddy as in Summer, are\nthe seasons of greatest social activity in\nthe isolated Island republic.\nHn\nHP\nfflllHr HHeH^H.\nHr <mmmmsm\n.|H \"!y V\nBL L\nKAISER AS HE LOOKED WHEN\nSTILL GERMANY\u2019S RULER.\nat Newport or in the Adlrondacks have\n20 spare rooms and who live in an at\nmosphere of luxury far beyond that of\nthe present \"First Gentleman of Doom.\u201d\nAt 5 o\u2019clock we all had afternoon tea\nat the main chateau and were formally\npresented to the Empress Hermlne. The\nKaiser came afoot in the direction of\nour building a little before tea time,\nand, of course, I hurried my pace on\nseeing him. He has a tremendously\nstrong right hand, and, though I appre\nciated the warmth of his welcome, my\nfingers needed medical massage after\nthe first handshake. He required no\nIntroduction to my wife, who dropped\nhim a curtsy like something out of an\neighteenth century minuet. That little\n1 turn was a surprise for me\u2014she had\nbeen practicing it in secret.\nPresented to Empress.\nEmpress Hermlne received us on the\nsteps of the big house, and, of course,\nI fell in love with her at once.\nWhy?\nBecause, in the first place, she is\nmotherly. She had two of her children\nwith her. She is wholly without man\nnerisms\u2014or perhaps I can make my\npoint clearer by stating frankly that\nshe placed her guests Immediately at\ntheir ease\u2014and I may add that in the\npresence of the Kaiser's first wife I\nwas never allowed to forget that she\nwas first, last and all the time the\n1 Empress of Deutschland \u00fcber Allea.\nHere my wife dropped a second\ncurtsy of such depth as alarmed me\nlest her knee, hinges collapse\u2014and here\nafter T shall not mention this purely\nformal matter which has at Doom\nvastly less importance than would have\n(Continued on Fourth Page.)\nThe recollection of its decisive Inter\nvention in 1917 \u201cto assure the salva\ntion of democracy\u201d evidently still domi\nnates all the other sentiments bom of\npost-war difficulties, which difficulties\nsuch feats as those of Col. Lindbergh\nand of Admiral Byrd sufficed to rele\ngate to the background In the day's\nnews.\nIt is especially since these feats that\nFrenchmen have turned unrestrictedly\ntoward the United States. Many are\nthe books treating of America which\nhave benefited by this vogue. Since\nthat forerunner, Andre Siegfried\u2019s \"The\nUnited States Today\u201d; all new docu\nmentation \u2014whether it consists of such\npolitical works as Andre Tardieu\u2019s \u201cBe\nfore the Obstacle: America and Our\nselves.\u201d and Romler\u2019s \u201cWho Will Be\nMaster: Europe or America?\u201d or\nwhether it consists of purely literary\nworks such as those of Paul Morand,\nor historical such as those of Firmin\nRoz \u2014all new documentation is wel\ncomed as throwing light on the capti\nvating spectacle of a great people in\nthe process of finding its path and\nperhaps of \u201ccreating in the modern\nworld a new conception of production\nand of life.\u201d\nNewspapers and magazines, especially\nfinancial organs, are devoting more and\nmore space to news and comments re\ngarding the political, economic and so\ncial life of the American people. The\nbulletins issued by American banks are\ncurrently reproduced and followed by a\nfaithful public, which, by the way, had\na large part in the vicissitudes of Wall\nStreet, and In addition a very impor\ntant American colony entertains in\nParis with high French society, in all\nthe artistic, financial or literary flelds,\nclose relations which contribute much\nin the very deep sentiments of amity\nbetween the two peoples.\nInfluence* on Public.\nWhat matters It, after that, if a jour\nnalist like \u201cPertinax,\u201d who professes\nnationalism, subjects these sentiments\nto the cold shower of a series of acidu\nlated articles, or if the satire of a stage\nplay, as in \"The Weak Sex.\u201d is directed\nto the cosmopolitanism of transatlantic\nhotels?\n.The vogue In France remains none\nthe less influenced to an extraordinary\ndegree by American films, American\nautomobiles and American Jazz. Even\nbefore the entry of the United States\ninto the war an actor like Charlie\nChaplin enjoyed immense popularity in\nFrance, where he is still regarded as an\nunrivaled genius of the films.\nFrench customs have been modified\nmuch more than Is believed generally\nby what has transpired of the mental\nity and the sporting spirit of Americans\nwhich matches in the ring or on the\ntennis court have frequently brought\nInto the spotlight.\nNevertheless, there will always sub\nsist a very great difference between\nthese two peoples, both fond of humor\nand of cordiality. Whereas the one has\na social mentality which is very con\nformist and deeply religious, the other\nis Individualistic to the highest degree.\nThe Frenchman is par excellence the\nfriend of diversity, and he does not fear\nany longer, as did his ancestors the\nGat*ls, that the heavens may fall on\nhis head.\n(Copyright. 1930.)\nI\nEditorial Page j\nBUSINESS PLAYS LITTLE\nPART IN CONGRESS RACES\nConnection With Politics in This Years\nCampaign Is Held to Be Less\nThan Ever Before.\nBY MARK SULLIVAN.\nTHE purpose of this article is to\nsay something about the pres\nent state of the times \u2014\u201cthe\ntimes\u201d in the business sense\u2014\n\u201cbad times,\u201d \u201cgood times.\u201d As\nrespects appropriateness, the topic hard\nly needs apology; a good many folks are\ntalking about it, thinking about it, writ\ning about it. It is related to politics,\nto the campaign now on to determine\nwhether the Democrats or the Repub\nlicans shall control the next Congress.\nThe state of the times, in an economic\nsense, is always associated with politics.\nFrequently the connection is forced, un\nreal, chiefly psychological. We find\nGeorge Washington, while he was Presi\ndent, in one of his letters complaining\napprehensively that he was in for a\nrough period because a current drought\nwas sure to make crops bad.\nThe connection of the present depres\nsion with politics is less than one would\nnormally expect; that is, there is less\ncharging of the depression up against\npolitics than is commonly the case.\nThere is some of it, but much less than\nusually happens.\nIn the 1907 depression (which was\nmuch like the present one, except that\nthe 1907 one was accompan:*! d> a\ncurrency famine, impossible rtow), tht\nthen President Roosevelt and \u201cbig busi\nness\" went at each other hammer and\ntongs. Business, especially big business,\nangry at Roosevelt for many reasons,\ncharged Roeseelt with responsibility\nfor the panic. Roosevelt retorted that\nbusiness brought it on itself. Business\nr and politics exchanged the usual pot\nand kettle epithets.\nBusiness, charging Roosevelt with the\npanic, was able to creat a public psy\nchology in which an important news\npaper called Roosevelt the \u201cgreatest\npanicmaker in history.\u201d and the New\nYork Sun, able morning newspaper of\nthat day, addressed Roosevelt thus:\n\u201cHail, Caesar! We who are about to\nr bust salute thee!\u201d Roosevelt was not\nthe man to let that go by without\nnotice. He retorted in a speech he\nmade at Provincetown, Mass., that big\nbusiness had brought on the depression\nItself, had brought it on deliberately.\nRoosevelt said that big business was\nangry at him because of his \u201ctrust\nbusting,\u201d and in order to discredit him\nhad precipitated panic.\nNeither Proved Accurate.\nNeither the charge made by big busi\nness nor the retort made by Roosevelt\nwas accurate. The depression of 1907\nwas \u201cin the cards\"; it was due to\narrive as the resultant of several causes.\nOne of the principal causes was the\nlack of a national banking system. That\nlack has since been remedied. We now\nhave the Federal Reerve System. Be\ncause we have that this depression has\nI not been accompanied and cannot be\naccompanied by any currency famine.\nTo this extent the present depression\nI cannot be as disastrous as the 1907 one.\nBut the 1907 panic was due to come.\nThe wise leaders of finance, the gray\np haired old gentlemen who had been in\nbusiness for more than 20 years, knew\nit had to come. Any one can look up\nthe New York newspapers of more than\na year preceding the 1907 panic and\nfind the venerable Jacob H. Schiff, then\nhead of Kuhn, Loeb Sc Co., saying that,\ndue to several causes, chiefly the lack j\nof a national banking system, the coun\ntry was \u201cdue for a panic compared to\nwhich previous ones would seem like\nchild play.\u201d\nTo complete the allusion to the 1907\npanic\u2014the crisis of it, the runs on\nbanks, with the banks unable to give\ndepositors the money that the deposi\ntors owned, occurred on October 22,\n1907. The ensuing Winter of 1907-08\nwas pretty bad\u2014very much worse than\nlast Winter. But by June, 1908, public\npsychology was fast getting back to\nnormal. Roosevelt was able to name\nTaft as his successor in the Republican\nnomination for the presidency, and in\nthe Fall Taft was elected over Bryan\nby rather more than a normal major\nity. The Senate and House continued\nto remain in the hands of the party\u2014i\nthe Republicans that had been in power I\nwhen the depression occurred.\nThe net of this part of the analogy\nis that there is no reason to expect\nthat because of the business depression\nCongress will be turned over to the\nDemocrats next Fall. One need not be\nso limited, one might put it, with some\nreservation, that there is no reason\nto expect that for any reason or all\nreasons Congress will be turned over to\nthe Democrats.\nDemocratic Senate Scouted.\nOs the two bodies that compose Con\ngress, one, the Senate, is about as cer\ntain as anything can be in politics to\nremain Republican\u2014Republican, that is,\ncounting the Progressive or insurgent\nRepublicans as part of the Republican\nmajority that organizes the Senate.\nTo put the case in figures, the Demo\ncrats have now 39 Senators out of a\ntotal of 96. To have a majority, to be\nable to control the Senate for them\nselves, and to organize it and control\nits committees \u2014to do that the Demo\ncrats would need to gain 10 more in\norder to have a majority, 49. They\ncannot possibly do it. None of their\nleaders expects to do it. In the sena-\ntorlal elections next Fall the Democrats\nmight readily gain as many as three.\nThey might even, if there were a tre-\nmendous landslide, gain as many as\nsix. But they cannot gain 10. And\nthe present fact is that nobody sees any\nlandslide in the making. The net of\nwhich is that in the next Senate about 1\nthe best the Democrats can hope is to\nhave 42, which Is seven less than a\nmajority.\nAs respects the House, the conditions\nfavoring the Republicans are not quite\nso convincing: that is, while we can say\nwith practically mathematical positive\nness that the Democrats cannot gain\ncontrol of the Senate, the positiveness\nin the case of the House is not quite\nso mathematical. Yet the writer of this\narticle does not know any Democratic\nleader who has any firm expectation of\nhis party winning control of the House\nin the November elections. Democratic\nleaders and Republican leaders both\nagree that in the House, as in the Sen\nate, the Democrats will make very con\nsiderable gains. But they both agree\nalso that the gains will je short of\nenough to turn the House over to the j\nDemocrats.\nThe total membership of the House is\n435. Making a rough allowance as to I\na few vacancies existing and regarding\nthe one Parmer-Labor member as a\nDemocrat, there are 267 Republicans to\n168 Democrats. This is a Republican\nmajority of 99. In order to reverse that\nmajority the Democrats would have to\ngain a minimum of 50 seats. It can\nhardly be done. It would take a land\nslide and there is no evidence of a land\nslide. The Democrats will make gains,\nwithout a doubt in the world, very con\nsiderable gains. The maximum Demo\ncratic gain that I have heard any Demo\ncratic leader seriously claim or any\nRepublican leader concede, is less than\n40. And even if the Democrats should\nwin this maximum of 40 additional\nseats the Republicans would still have\na narrow yet comfortable majority of\nroughtly, 20.\nAll this is without regard to the busi\nness depression. So far as any observer\ncan see, the depression does not figure\nV\nmuch in the calculations of political\nmanagers, nor, apparently, in the minds\nof the voters. For whatever reason the\nDemocrats seem less disposed than is\nusual with the party out of power to\nblame the business depression on the\nparty in power. There is less political\nagitation of this kind, less political cap\nitalizing of \u201chard times\u201d than has been\nthe rule during previous depressions.\nIssue Remains Doubtful.\nThe Democrats for the moment create\nan impression of uncertaint* on their\npart as to what issue they expect\" to\nemphasize. Up to the of the\nactual passage of the tariff bill prac\ntically the whole of the Democratic\npublicity laid emphasis on the tartn\nSince that event there has been a defi\nnite and striking. phenomenon, what\never its meaning nay be. The Demo\ncrats in an obvtjas manner have \u201claid\noff\u201d the tariff Wot only the Democrats.\nThe two largest chains of newspapers\nin Ame***A\u00bb, which, while the tariff was\npendhV lashed it with fury, have had\nsirw the bill was passed, Almost lit\ntftilly not a word to say about the tariff.\nWhat that means is hard to a\\y. Per\nhaps it may be recognition that the\ntariff could not possibly be the cause,\nor even a cause, of the business depres\nsion. In any event we should be able\nto set *ectty soon Just what issues the\nDemocrats expert, wj raise and empha\nsize in the campaign that shortly will\nbe under way.\nTo turn from the political aspect of\nthe present expression, to consider it\nin the light in which nearly everybody\nlooks upon it, to speculate upon how\nit will express itself in the future state\nof business, ex-President Coolldge the\nother day referred to some previous de\npressions and said:\n\"The important fact is that the coun\ntry went on developing wealth\nincreased greatly.\u201d\nIt would be safe to be even more\nspeciflc'and more emphatic. The longest\nperiod of lowering prices this country\nhas ever known was from the early\n\u20197os to the late \u20199Gs. Yet it was during\njust that period that the biggest busi\nnesses and the greatest fortunes this\ncountry has ever known were built up.\nIt was during precisely that period that\npractically the whole of the early oil\nbusiness was built up and John D.\nRockefeller made not merely the start\nof his fortune, but quite probably as\nmuch as half of all he has today. Not\nonly Mr. Rockefeller but scores and\nhundreds of others in the oil business.\nIt was during that period that the steel\nbusiness grew up\u2014the steel business as\nwe know it today in contrast with the\npreceding and now partly eclipsed Iron\nbusiness. It was during that period\nthat Mr. Carnegie made his fortune and\nthe components of what in 1901 became\nthe United States Steel Corporation\nwere built up. It was during that pe\nriod, in spite of some Intervals diffi\ncult for farmers, that land in the West\nern States rose in value from a few\ndollars an acre to upward of a hundred.\nNot to prolong the illustrations, the\nimportant and practical point having\nreference to the present is that low\nI prices for goods, which is the outstand\ning mark of the present condition, do\nnot necessarily make for lack of busi\nness activity or lack of prosperity. On#\nmight reasonably assert the contrary\u2014\ni that low prices of goods make for great\nvolume of business. The proof is near\nat hand. The period Just behind us,\nfrom 1920 to 1930, was a period, on the\nwhole, of low or lowering prices. Yet\nthat was precisely the period of the\ngreatest prosperity this country has ever\nknown.\nTrade Gains After Decline.\nWhat happens is this: Over long pe\nriods, sometimes as long as 20 years or\nmere, prices of goods tend downward.\nBut the decline seems to take place In\na particular way. It takes the form of\na sudden and rather drastic drop, fol\nlowed by several years of roughly sta\nbilized prices on the new level. At the\nend of several years there may be a\nnew and considerable drop, followed\nagain by several years at the new level.\nThe comparatively brief period of the\ni drastic drop is attended by very much\nreduced volume of business. Thereafter,\nonce the new level is established, busi\nness goes forward with an increasing\nmomentum that becomes something like\na fury of activity.\nThat is what has happened during\nthe last 10 years in the United States.\nAbout 1920 there was a stringent fall\nin prices, accompanied by a severe halt\nin business activity: then ensued nearly\n10 years of the greatest volume of busi\nness and the greatest prosperity the\ncountry has ever known. Then came a\nnew drastic drop in prices, in the midst\nof which we now are.\nAbout the duration of this business\ndepression there has been much pre\ndiction. One would not do a service to\nadd to the quantity of it. But there\nis present at this moment a concrete\ncondition\u2014the consumption of goods is\nmuch greater for the moment than the\nproduction of goods.\nThe consumption of many forms of\ngoods is going on almost as usual. That\nis shown by the figures for chain-store\nsales, which are less than 5 per cent\nbelow last year. At the same time the\ndecline in the production of goods, as\nmeasured by the reports of manufac\nturers, is from 10 to 15 per cent, at\nleast, below last year.\nWhat this means, sooner or later, is\na sudden realization of a kind of famine\nin goods, followed by a hurried buying\nof goods on the part of retailers and\nother dealers, resulting, perhaps, in a\nslight elevation of prices over present\n1. .T .1. AM J 4ln 4# Ms a an las\nlevels and thereafter, if we can Judge\nby precedent, a new and prolonged pe\nriod of constantly Increasing business\nactivity at the new level of prices.\n\nTokio's Strict Dance\nHall Laws Criticized\nTokio's laws strictly limiting the\nnumber of public dance halls in the\ncapital and closing at 11 o\u2019clock at\nnight those which are permitted to\noperate are characterized as unrea\nsonable by the chief of the foreign\nj section of the metropolitan police board.\nJ He says that one of the principal rea\nsons tourists do not like to stay for\nlong in Tokio is that Its night life is\ndrab compared to some of the other\nmetropolises of the Far East. The\npresence of a few more dance halls in\nthe center of town would provide a\nwholesome form of entertainment which\nwould be beneficial to both residents\nand visitors, the official said. Recent\nactivity on the part of the government\nto attract tourists to Japan has run\ninto handicaps furnished by the police,\nwho maintain that dance halls and\nsuch forms of entertainment aren\u2019t good\nfor public morals and should not be\nallowed Just for the sake of a few\ntourists The opinion of the chief of\nthe foreign section was received with\npleasure by the general public, although\nno drastic changes in the present reg\nulations are expected until a few more\nof the police officials are similarly con\nvinced.","height":"25503","width":"19860"}}
